    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc" resp="#VM #AA">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested"><name>Ὦλε</name> <name>Πά<unclear>π</unclear><supplied reason="undefined" evidence="previouseditor">ιε</supplied></name>
                    <lb n="2"/><name>Ἀγάθαρχε</name></persName>
                    <lb n="3"/>χαῖρε
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus" resp="#AA">
                <listApp>
                    <app><note>Text from autopsy</note></app>
                    <app loc="1"><note>The damage to the top right of line 1, might be reconstructed as pi, or tau (with a short crossbar) followed by another letter (perhaps iota). That the final two letters were iota and epsilon is recorded in IG as extant on the stone.</note></app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#AA">
                <p>Olos Papios Agatharchos, farewell.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" resp="#AA">
                <p>The praenomen Olos, derived from the Latin Aulus, is attested elsewhere epigraphically (but not in Sicily). If the restoration is correct, Papios is the first epigraphic instance of the transcription of Papius into Greek. Agatharcos is a common Greek name. Korhonen notes that this inscription was never transported and sent back from Rome, as recorded in IG (with bibliography).</p>         
            </div>
